\begin_layout Itemize
CD account 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
A certificate of deposit in US, but otherwise known as Time deposit.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
This is basically a locked-in account.
 It means that you have some money in it, but if you pull it our, you will
 lose all interest you have been making on that.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
It is a type of savings account and it is an interest-bearing bank deposit
 with a specified period of maturity.
 But here, however, unlike a classic savings account, the client arranges
 it for a predetermined period of time and interest.
 A client must not withdraw or deposit money for the agreed period.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
401k 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Retirement plan, paid by your employer and also employee (50:50).
 For example, when I put $20 into retirement plan (before taxes!) from my
 salary, my employer will match that and will put also $20 (or maybe even
 more).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A 401(k) is an employer sponsored retirement plan that is eligible to employees
 where they can make salary reduction contributions on a pre/post-tax basis.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\emph on
Individual Retirement Account (IRA)
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Account you can set up via a broker such as Fidelity or Charles Schwab.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
You will put your money to such account and you can invest it into for example
 bonds or stocks.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
There are 3 types of IRA: 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\emph on
Traditional IRA
\emph default
 - money has not been taxed, but it will be taxed when you will put it out
 for your retirement time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\emph on
Roth IRA 
\emph default
- in this IRA, the money has been already taxed when you put them into that
 account, and when you want to pull them, you don't have to tax it any more.
 And you are never forced to take your money out.
 In comparison to traditional IRA, in Roth IRA, there are some limits in
 how much money you can put there.
 To Traditional IRA, you can contribute whatever much you like.
 Maybe Roth IRA is better, you never know if taxes won't be higher in the
 future.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\emph on
Rollover IRA 
\emph default
- you have for example 401k with an employer, you will leave that employer,
 and if you will keep your money there you won't pay any taxes.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
